    "actor_description": "My chest aches, but it's the good kind—warm and full and almost too much, like my ribs can barely hold it. I don't want anything to change. Just this: watching them, breathing the same air, letting this tender heaviness pool behind my sternum until it spills into my throat, my face, my hands. I could stay here forever and it would be enough.",
    "description_text": "{actor} goes still in a way that suggests deep attention rather than restraint. Their expression opens—warm-eyed, undefended—and they seem to forget themselves, caught in quiet observation. Every gesture becomes gentler, more deliberate, as if they're aware they're holding something breakable in their chest.",
    "alternate_descriptions": {
        "auditory": "Someone's voice drops into something tender and unhurried—words spacing out, tone warming from the inside. They sound like they're speaking to something precious, careful not to break the moment with volume or rush.",
        "tactile": "The air around someone grows noticeably softer, their presence less defined by movement and more by this radiating gentleness. Touch, if it comes, would be reverent—slow hands, careful pressure, like they know exactly how delicate this feeling is.",
        "limited": "{actor} looks quietly undone by tenderness—eyes soft and bright, expression open like a hand uncurling."
